{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608737/1958032301/0597.xml":{"full_text":"Spot Check Indicates\nRise in Unemployment\nBy tht Associated Press\nA spot check by the Associated Press showed yesterday\nthat unempolyment still is increasing in March in the Nation\u2019s\nmajor labor markets.\nThe sample, while not Nation-wide in scope, covered more\nthan a dozen of the biggest employment areas. It showed the\nIdle in these areas increased by about 150,000 from the middle\nof February to the middle of\nMarch.\nBut, like the first robin in the\nspring, there are some hopeful\nsigns. The survey data, together\nwith the Government\u2019s latest\nunemployment com pensation\nclaims figures, suggest the job\nless peak is close at hand and\nthere may be some decline in\nunemployment in April.\nJob Picture Now\nThe Job picture at the mo\nment appears to be this: Un\nemployment is still rising, but\nits upward momentum is rap\nidly slowing down. This is due\nto the usual spring employment\npickqp on farms and in other\noutdoor work as weather im\nproves. This improvement has\nbeen delayed this year because\nof late winter storms.\nBut an April decline in the\nnumber of jobless, unless it is\nquite substantial, would not\nspell an end to the recession.\nUnemployment normally drops\nby about 400,000 or 500,000 be\ntween February and April. And\navailable data indicates no de\ncline in March.\nAn April pickup in construc\ntion, farming and other out\ndoor work could reduce some\nwhat the over-all national un\nemployment total\u2014last counted\nby the Government at 5,173,000\nas of mid-February.\nBut the seasonal gain in out\ndoor work would not signal an\neconomic revival unless there\nis also Job improvement in the\nauto and plane factories, steel\nmills and other types of manu\nfacturing and mining\u2014the hard\ncore of the current economic\ntrouble.\nPennsylvania Outlook\nIn Pennsylvania, where the\nlast jobless tally was 464.000,\nWilliam L. Batt, Jr., State Sec\nretary of Labor and Industry, 1\nexpressed doubt that a seasonal\nupswing in construction really\nwould bite deeply into the\nState\u2019s Jobless problem.\n\u2018The is what\nhappens in factory employ\nment,\u201d Mr. Batt said. \"What\nwe need most is for men to get\nback to work in heavy manu\nfacturing. The steel industry\nis important. As long as it\u2019s\noperating at only about 50 per\ncent of capacity we\u2019re going to\nhave a problem.\u201d\nThe Federal Reserve Board\nsaid a few days ago that pro\nduction, employment, income\nand retail sales all had declined\nin February. It noted further\nearly March declines in auto\nproduction as well as in min\neral output, including crude oil.\nThe Government\u2019s job data\nfor' March will not be known\nuntil the second week of April.\nA month ago President Eisen\nhower said there was every in\ndication March would com\nmence to see the start of a\npickup in job opportunities,\nmarking \u201cthe beginning of the\nend of the downturn.\u201d Later,\nGabriel Hauge, his economic\nassistant, said he expected to\nsee the downturn \"slow to a\nstop\" between April and July.\nThe latest Labor Department\nreport shows that in the week\nof March 8 there were 3,274,-\n800 jobless among workers in\nsured by the unemployment\ncompensation system. Only\nabout two-thirds of all the\nNation\u2019s workers are covered\nunder the system.\nThe 3,274,800 figure repre-\nPlans for Art Museum\nMay Have to Be Delayed\nPlans for a museum of American art In the current Civil\nService Commission building may have to be postponed in\ndefinitely because of Congressional action killing four new\nFederal office buildings in the District.\nA bill authorizing transfer of the CSC building to the\nSmithsonian Institution to house the $lO million National\nCollection of Fine Arts is on\nPresident Eisenhower\u2019s desk,\nawaiting his signature.\nBut before the building can\nbe transferred, the Civil Service\nCommission must have new\noffices.\nThe commission was sched\nuled to move into Federal office\nbuilding No. 9, slated for con\nstruction early next year. It\nwill be west of the Interior\nDepartment on Nineteenth\nstreet N.W. between E street\nand Virginia avenue. The cost\nis $22 million.\nHowever, the House Appro\npriations Committee refused\nFriday to provide funds for\nthis building and three others\nbecause, it said, Washington\nis better off economically than\nother sections of the country.\nF. Moran McConihe, commis\nsioner of public buildings for\nthe Oeneral Services Adminis\ntration, said yesterday the com\nmittee\u2019s action means that\nOSA\u2019s plans for new buildings\nwill just have to wait.\nOther plans for the razing of\nwartime temporary buildings\nand the completion of the Fed\neral Triangle also will be set\nback, since there will be no\nspace for Federal employes in\npermanent structures unless\nALL IN EAR!\nWORN* ENTIRELY 'iN\nnothing worn anywhere\nSONOTONE\n901 WASHINGTON BLDG.\n1435 G ST. N.W. Dl. 7-0921\n\u00a3^om^n^Pfco\u00bb^o\u00bb^W\u00abte^N\u00bbe^foii^o\u00dfinoiistrofio^^f^OW/jotio*^\nJOBLESS RATE\ni HERE IS LOWER\nTHAN FOR U. S.\ni The latest figures on\nWashington area unem-\nI ployment released last\ni week showed 3.5 per cent\nof the area\u2019s workers were\nunemployed in February.\nThis compared to Labor\nDepartment figures show\ning a Nation-wide average\nof 6.7 per cent.\nThe District office of the\nUnited States Employment\nService reported the Wash\nington area jobless total at\ni 26,500, a four-year high.\nUnemployment In the\narea had increased 3,200 in\nFebruary, but this was less\nthan the 3,700 unemploy\nment Increase registered in\nthe same period last year,\ni The service reported most\nof the local jobless were m\nthe construction Industry,\nhard hit by heavy snow\nstorms this winter.\nsents a slight decline from the\nprior week\u2019s total, but an in\ncrease of about 138,000 over the\nI week of February 15, when the\nGovernment took its last over\nall tally of the unemployed.\nSome of the unemployment\nchanges among insured workers\nin key States, with figures for\nMarch 8 listed first, followed in\nparentheses by the February 15\nweek totals:\nCalifornia 311,303 (315,843);\nOregon 44,244 (45,424); Wash\nington 62,134 (71,417); New\nYork 384,721 (361,439); Penn\nsylvania 332,098 (309.604); Ohio\n208,650 (202,184); Illinois 172,-\n672 (163.644); Indiana 88,271\n1(87,571); Missouri 62,358 (65,-\n882); Rhode Island 27,445 (26.-\n317); Alabama 46,575 (46,310),\nand Texas 72,926 (65,460).\nThe AP spot check showed\nseasonal job improvement in\nCalifornia, Washington and\nOregon, the West Coast States\nwhich have been hard hit. Ply-1\nwood plants in Oregon and!\nWashington which had closed\nbecause of low prices have now\nreopened, and timber activities\nare picking up. Boeing Air\ncraft at Seattle has delayed\nscheduled layoffs.\nBoston reports the job situa\ntion in the six-State New Eng\nland area is static with a slight\nincrease in insurance-covered\nunemployment between mid-\nFebruary and mid-March. The;\nincrease was heaviest in Con\nnecticut where the legislature\nis in special session considering\nanti-recession proposals.\nIn New York, figures for un\nemployment claims shot up sub\nstantially in both the State\nand New York City between\nmid-February and early March.\nMartin W. Wilmington, New\nYork City economist, said the\nMarch picture \"shows some\nchange for the worse.\u201d\nIn Michigan, center of the\nhard-pressed auto industry,\nmid-March unemployment was\nestimated by State officials at.\n420.000 for the State and 230,-!\n000 so r Detroit alone. The\nState-wide figure was up 62,000\nfrom mid-February. Current\nunemployment represents 14.3\nper cent of the labor force, 15.1\nper cent of Detroit\u2019s.\nthe new buildings are erected.\nThree of the four new bulld\nj ings were to have been built in\nthe Southwest redevelopment\ni area.\nThe Southwest projects re\njected were:\nFederal office building No. 6\nto be bounded by Fourth, Sixth\nand C streets S.W. and Mary\nland avenue, west of the De\npartment of Health, Education\nand Welfare at a cost of $14.7\nmillion.\nFederal office building No. 8\nto be built as a combined lab\nj oratory and offices for the Fed\neral Food and Drug Adminis\ntration immediately southwest\n1 of the HEW building on Second,\nThird and D streets S.W. at a\ncost of (15.9 million.\nFederal office building No.\n10, in reality two buildings, on\nthe Mall along Independence\navenue between Sixth and\nNinth' streets N.W. at a cost\nof (40.7 million.\nConstriction on all three was\nto have started early next year.\nThe committee also refused\nto provide $1.2 million for\nplanning of Federal office\nbuilding No. 7 on Lafayette\ni square across from the White\ni House. This would house mem\ni bers of the Executive offices.\nJr\"*'*\u2019*.\u2022\ny ft.,\njtM y\nI\n'6\n/a w Hi\nUTTLEST STOCKHOLDER WAITS\nOwner of 10 shares, Kevin W. O\u2019Toole, 2, son of Mr.\nand Mrs. William D. O\u2019Toole, awaits annual meeting\nof stockholders* of the Stecher-Traung Lithograph\nCorp. at Rochester, N. Y. He sits at big desk in the\nexecutive committee room under a portrait of Louis\nTraung, a former owner.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nWall Street Experts\nGive Stock Mart Views\nNEW YORK, Mar. 22 (JP).\u2014\nThe stock market has gained\nj since last October while busi\nness has been going downhill.\nWhy?\nDoes this mean that the mar\nket is fulfilling its barometric\ntradition of forecasting a busi\nness upturn in four to six\nmonths?\nNot necessarily, say some\nWall Street experts; the stock\nmarket frequently has been\nvery misleading as a business\nbarometer.\nBut the market has advanced\nsince last October 22 when it\nfell to its lowest point since\nJanuary 1955. This has puzzled\nmany investors.\nThe rise is ascribed to a tech\nnical recovery usual after a\nsharp drop as well as to easing\nof money, hope of tax cuts and\nother anti-recession measures\nbeing developed in Washington.\nGerald M. Loeb, partner in\nE. F. Hutton 8c Co, said: \u201cThe\nstock averages are up, and up in\nthe face of the most widespread\nbearish news on business. This\nnews is worldwide.\nSelling High\n\u201cMost stocks,\u201d he added, \u201care\nselling high on the basis of a\ncontinuation of their fourth\nquarter earnings. They are\nhigher still if compared with\nan annual earnings rate cal\nculated at four times the first\nquarter results. It means the\nmarket expects that the Gov\nernment will spend more and\ntax less.\u201d\nThe record shows that since\nOctober the market has gone\nforward on news such as Presi\ndent Eisenhower\u2019s reaffirming\nhis faith in the economy; on\nthe lowering of the discount\nrate by the Federal Reserve\nBoard; the cut in margin re\nquirements to 50 per cent from\n70 per cent; the launching of\nthe Explorer earth satellite;\nthe drop in interest rates; and 1\non hopes of pump-priming and\ntax cutting.\nAfter striking a recovery\npeak on February 4, the market\ndropped irregularly until Feb\nruary 25, almost cancelling-out j\nits 1958 gains. But industrial\nstocks then went ahead for\neight straight sessions, nearly\nSPINET and CONSOLE c=3JTT\u00ae3I\ni pianos wmm\nV MONTHLY AND UP\nK Plus Hauling Charges \u2014yl l\nH. M. CABLE WINTER STEINWAY \"\u2018\"rvT\u2122\u201d\"\nCHICKERING MASON HAMLIN m ,\u201ed\nWURLITZER HUNTINGTON BREMEN o\u00bbr 100 i.\nBRADBURY MUSETTE CABLE-NELSON i\u201e m r\u201e m\nSTORY CLARK GEORGE STECK \u2022sutei-Nrcfeese\nJORDAN'S\nDOWNTOWN SILVER SPRING ARLINGTON EREDERICKSSURG\n13th I G Sts., N.W. 9332 Co. Ave. 5169 Lie Hwy. 2415 Piinccss Ann* St.\n_STwli\u00df\u00a33 9jOO_jUnipof 51105 KEnmort 8-5060 ESses 3-7472\nWith No Musical Training I\nYou Play Beautifully on the \\y\nHAMMOND\nChord Organ\nAnyone Can Play, Without Lessons\nYou con enjoy playing rich, full- lADnAkI^C\nchorded music after just a few\nminutes basic Instruction.' Thou- mu, .tabic\nsonds of people have leorned to F U TW\nrelax ond hove a thrilling new in- Cor. Ufh flr G Sts., ST. 3-9400\nterest in life when they started 9332 Go. Ave., S. JU. 5-1105\nplaying the Chord Organ. Phone 5169 Lee Hwy., All, KE. 8-5060\nony of our stores ond ask about our 2415 Princess Anne St.,\nFREE HOME TRIAL and Fredericksburg, ES. 3-7472\nUnTAL-FURCHASE PLANS ri OPEN EVES. In S. S. and Art.\nreaching the February 4 peak\nbefore backsliding.\nOs the eight-day rise, Eldon\nA. Grimm, vice president of\nWalston 8c Co., said: \u201cThat\nadvance was due to covering by\nover-extended short sellers and\nto hopes of massive pump\npriming such as public works\nand tax cuts.\nExplanations Given\n\"The market\u2019s ability to hold\nabove the lows of last October\nand a subsequent rally which\nwould go above the February\n4 high would be a clue to an\nupturn,\u201d said Mr. Grimm.\n\u201cThat would mean that the\nmarket was forecasting an\nearly upturn in business.\u201d\nRalph A. Rotnem, partner in\nHarris, Upham 8c Co., said:\nI \u201cThe market\u2019s recovery since\n'last October has been nothing\nI more than an average rise af\nter a drop such as last fall\u2019s.\nIn fact, the rise to date has\n'been sub-normal.\u201d\nHe recalled that following\nthe great crash of November\n1929 the market recovered 48\nper cent of its lost ground by\nApril 1930. The advance was\nmisleading as a token of a\nbusiness upturn because the\ndepression worsened and stocks\nddin\u2019t hit bottom until 1932\nwhen the depression was at its\nworst.\nThe recent recovery since\nOctober of about 40 per cent\nof the losses since the July top\ncannot be taken as a reliable\nforecast of a prompt business\nupturn, Mr. Rotnem said.\nRange Predicted\nIn terms of the Dow-Jones|\nIndustrial average, Mr. Rotnem\npredicted that the market will\nrange between 360 and 460 this\nyear. The February 4 recoverv\nhigh was 458.65. If his predlc-:\ntion is accurate, lt means the\nmarket has a sharp drop in\nprospect.\nAt the start of 1957, incident\nally, Mr. Rotnem forecast a\nrange of 420 to 520 in the Dow\navreage. The actual high was\n520.77 and the low was 419.79.\nHarry D. Comer, partner at\nPaine, Webber, Jackson 8c Cur\ntis. took a similar view of the\nsnapback since October. The\n'SB Graduates\nFace Decline\nIn Job Offers\nCollege seniors long accus\ntomed to finding upon gradua\ntion that the world is their\noyster may have to settle for\nlesser fare this June.\nJob opportunities are fewer,\nstudent placement directors at\nGeorgetown, George Washing\nton, Maryland, Howard, Catho\nlic and American Universities\nsaid yesterday.\nLewis Knebel, director of the\nUniversity of Maryland student\nplacement office, reported that\n20 per cent of the companies\nscheduled to send representa\ntives onto the College Park\ncampus this year to Interview\nstudents have canceled the ap\npointments.\nA similar decline was reported\nat Catholic and Howard Uni\nversities. William J. Cannon of\nthe Catholic University place\nment office and Mrs. Marian\nCoombs of Howard each re\nported that there cancellations\nwere running about the same.\nAn even more drastic cancel\nlation rate was reported by Mrs.\nBeverly Currier, student place\nment director at George\nWashington University, where\nthe number of campus inter\nviews scheduled is down from\nlast year\u2019s all-time high of 184\nto a total of 118 for this year.\nFewer Cancellations\nRobert W. Jones and Mrs.\nEstelle Guinane of the Amer\nican and Georgetown University\nplacement offices reported that\ntheir schools also were suffer\ning from cancellations, but to\na lesser extent than the other\nschools.\nAmerican University has had\nonly four cancellations out of\nmore than 60 scheduled, while\nGeorgetown reported only a\n\u201cfew\u201d cancellations.\nMost of these cancellations,\nthe placement directors agree,\nhave come from companies en\ngaged in producing durable\ngoods and processed raw ma\nterials such as the automobile,\naircraft and steel industries.\nBut even some usually energetic\nrecruiters\u2014such as insurance\ncompanies, for example\u2014are\nmaking cancellations this year.\nSome companies such as\nU. S. Steel have stopped re\ncruiting for non-technical\nworkers altogether, and most\nof the slump-ridden automobile\ncompanies have followed suit or\nhave seriously curtailed their\nrecruiting activities.\nSit Back and Wait\nAll placement directors inter\nviewed asserted that many of\nthe companies that have can\nzigs and zags of the financial\ngrass, he and other experts\ndemonstrated, show an aston\nishing resemblance to that of\nthe 1937-38 bear market. If the\nparallel continues, a sharp dip\nis in the cards, before recovery.\nMr. Comer, as early as Sep\ntember 1956, was in the fore\nfront on Wall Street predicting\nan end to the 1949-56 bull mar\nket.\n\u201cBarring a real, all-out at\ntack on the recession, I don\u2019t\nexpect a bull market this year,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Comer. \u201cI think the\nbear market is about half over,\nif it follows the normal pattern.\nBut the government might turn\nit around if they hit it with\neverything they\u2019ve got. I have\nmy doubts through.\u201d\npw rwrj\nf fit Store hour, daily 10 a.m. to b pin g ,1\nr 7 Corner, atoning ahopping 1 Sj\n2 Monday. Thursday and Friday until 9:30 p in 1\n11\nSuits of /Tropical Worsted j\n2 Cut from a fine tropical worsted, loomed\nin England, tkese good looking suits are n\n5 cool and comfortable for spring and sutnmer\nHand-tailored by Baker for additional\ncomfort and ease of fit. \\\\l\\\nG e)\n2 Attractive patterns and colors X\ny 120.00 S\nMen Clothing, Second Floor;\n7 Corners Men\u2019s Shop\nS Julius Garfinckel &Co 2\nr ft F Street ourteentli 7 Corners, Virginia\nNAt, nal 8-7730 <L\n11 wxOll I\ncelled their campus interviews\nnow feel they can sit back and\nwait for Job-seeking graduates\nto come to them and thus they\ncut down on recruiting ex\npenses.\n\"At American University,\u201d\nMr. Jones said, \u201csome of the\nboys afe becoming wary of in\ndusrial firms and are beginning\nto swing over more to wanting\nto work for non-industrial con\ncerns. There has been more\ninterest in Insurance companies\nthis year than ever before.\u201d\nMr. Jones said that, of the\n20 to 30 students placed by his\noffice this year, most have gone j\nwith non-industrial firms.\nAt Maryland, however, Mr. j\nKnebel reported, most of the\nstudents are still seeking posi\ni tions with the big name corpor\nations.\n\u201cIn fact,\u201d he added, \u201cmany\nof our cancellations have come\nfrom lesser companies who were\ni disappointed by the lack of stu\ndent interest here.\u201d\nMr. Knebel said -the compa\nnies are making fewer Job of- j\nfers this year not only because\nof this higher acceptance ratio\nI but also because they* have\nfewer jobs to offer.\nAnother thing the colleges\nare expecting is that starting\ni salaries for college graduates\nwill be about the same this year\nj as last year.\n\u201cThis is in sharp contrast to\nthe upward spiral of salaries\nsince the end of World War II,\u201d\nMr. Jones of American Univer\nsity said.\nr Bright Spots, Too\nBut the picture isn\u2019t all dark.\nHere and there bright spots can\nbe found.\nFor example, all the stu\ndent placement directors inter\nviewed reported that company\nrepresentatives who have al\nready come for campus inter\nr views this year have indicated\nthey want to come back next\nyear.\ni \"I think,\u201d said Mrs. Currier\nof George Washington, \u201cthis\nindicates that businessmen ex\n-1 pect this recession to be only\ntemporary.\u201d\nDespite the heavy cancella\ntions of campus interviews,\nmost schools are still luring\nmore company representatives\non campus than they were four\nyears ago.\nGeorge Washington Univer\nsity, which saw companies cut\ntheir campus visits from 184 in\n1957 to 118 this year, still is\nabove its total for 1954 when\nonly 83 companies visited the\nG street school.\n\"There are plenty of jobs still\ni available.\u201d said Mrs. Guinane\nof Georgetown, \u201cthis recession\nsimply means that the seniors\nwill have to look harder to find\na Job.\u201d\nDope Convict Swallows\nShave Powder, Dies\nA prisoner in the District\nJail died Friday night after\nswallowing a large quantity of\naftershave powder.\nThe man, Wilbert Fowler. 37.\nwas serving a 10-year sentence\ni for narcotics violations. He had\n)been confined to a maximum\nsecurity section after testifying\nfor the Government in another\nt recent narcotics case.\nLt. Charles Burns of the po\nlice homicide squad said the\ndeath was apparently suicide.\nThe coroner was expected to\nrule later.\nFowler apparently swallowed\nthe contents of two cans of\nthe face powder. It contained\nbarium sulfide and calcium hy\ndroxide, the latter an internal\npoison.\nFowler died at District Gen- I\neral Hospital shortly after being\ndiscovered ill in his cell. His\nlast address was 64 Fenton\nstreet N.W.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, Washington, D. C. M\nSDWDAT, StICS *3, IMS\njm\nA. S. JOHNSON CO.\nOFFERS FOR A\nLIMITED TIME ONLY\nTHE FAMOUS\nI TWIN (2) COMPRESSORS I\nI CENTRAL RESIDENTIAL I\nI AIR CONDITIONING I\nI FOR YOUR ENTIRE HOWE\nPRE-SEASON PRICE!\nAT A SAVINGS UP TO *IOO.OO\nm\nWarning\u2014Act Now! Limited Time Only\nNOTHING DOWN\n3 YEARS TO PAY!\nFIRST PAYMENT JUNE 1958\nThe Fabulous, Washington Tested and\nProven, Twin 2-H.P. Vornado Unit,\nGuaranteed to Cool Up to 1,400 Sq. Ft.,\nComplete with Duct Work, 5 Ceiling\nDiffusers, 1 Filtered Return, Wiring,\nThermostat, 3-Way Selector Switch.\nONE YEAR FREE SERVICE\nAND FIVE-YEAR FACTORY\nWARRANTEE!\nLarger Units for Larger Homes\nAt Similar Savings\nThe Same Payntent Plans\nThese Units Are Also Adaptable to\nCertain Types of Two-Story Houses\nand Furnace Tie-Ins\nInvestigate This Possibility!\nWHY PUT IT OFF?\nCALL NOW-TODAV, SUNDAY\nCALL HU. 3-5300\nREMEMBER ONLY Vornado has been proved in\neconomy and performance in HUNDREDS OF Washington\nhomes over THREE summer